mts.s:
For our project, we are planning on redesigning an existing website for a club on campus known as Students For Animals and Pets. The website currently has very basic information about the purpose of the club, some background on the officers, and a few photos of previous events. The overall layout is amateur and not up-to-date. Based upon our skill sets and availability, we decided that redesigning this website would be a good management project because it involves communication with the club and is doable within our time constraint.

Our goal for this project is to not only update this website to have more useful information for the students, but also possibly incorporate other forms of social media to encourage communication between club members and the board. In addition, we would like the updated website to emphasize the different programs and events this club has to offer, as well as showcase the overall purpose and vision of the club, Students for Animals and Pets (SFAP)
Other potential risks include the website crashing, not being manageable enough for the members after the website has been created.

The current situation with the Students For Animals and Pets (SFAP) website is that there is not enough content on the page to make members and visitors sufficiently informed about the club and the events that are happening there. Much of what is already provided on the club is out-of-date, and very minimal in terms of the amount of detail provided in weekly events. 
Our overall goal is to redesign the website into a more professional environment where members can retrieve up-to-date information regarding club meetings, events, news, while also being able to share their thoughts and give feedback in a chatroom feature. To make the information look more presentable, we intend on dividing up information that are related to one another  into various tabs so that users can easily locate the information that they are looking for (i.e. About Us, Membership, Gallery, Contact Us etc). Outside of cleaning up the information, we are also considering adding a calendar feature to display weekly meetings and weekend events, which helps the user visual all events more easily in comparison to the current design (i.e. being listed). We also intend on adding sign-up features for becoming a member, paying for membership and donating money to the club online via Paypal. Finally, in order to use these implemented features, we need to retrieve enough information about the club from current and past members and officers.

Stakeholders:

Club President
Club Members
Site Visitors
Website Manager

Potential Risks
	One of the largest risks that could occur from this website redesign is that the product may not turn out the way that the officers of the club have envisioned. For example, preliminary information may not accurately reflect or present the club appropriately. If this were to happen, the entire project would in a sense be considered a failure, because the customers are not satisfied with the product. The main source of this problem would be lack of communication with the current officers. 
	Other risks that could occur from this project range from problems with usability and feasibility. For usability, the main problem that could occur is that the officers of the club do not know how to use the website. As the developers, we are planning to design the website so that everything will be provided to them, and the officers only have to change or add a few details regularly to keep information up-to-date. However, we are assuming that current and future officers are somewhat tech-savvy. Under the circumstance that the officers are not tech-savvy at all, there is always the possibility that the website may not be used at all because it is not user-friendly enough. 
As for feasibility risks, the main problem would be not being able to finish the website in the given time, which is 8 weeks for this case. Other potential risks include the website crashing, having the page down for a long time which will make it unavailable for the members to use, having broken links to other web pages, such as the Facebook Group, as well as 3rd party websites that could be linked, such as Paypal for accepting membership and donations.
